{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_fogler_ver01/data/sn83030214/00206532592/1921011601/0451.xml":{"full_text":"Franklin Party\nTo Start Gtv's\nfeek of Thrift\nMemory of American Who\n|)id So Much for Amer?\nica Will Be Honored at\nStatue on His Birthday\n\nprogram h a Varied One\nRear Admiral Glennon Will\nRepresent U. S. Navy in\nCeremonies in Park Row\nTo-morrow-Ben Franklin's birthday\nJriU usher in Thrift Week, during\n-hid? the folk hereabouts will be\n.reed to heed the principles which the\n?gter.philosopher-statesman used to\n\"ffsUtue in Park Row, which\ndeclare to have worn a sternly\n???proving expression during the\ny few years of extravagant living,\n-ill be the goal to-morrow afternoon\n0f various organizations that are bent\n_B making amends to the revered\n?triot by placing wreaths at the\nJ?iuc*s base and publicly resolving to\nIk thrifty in 1921.\nRear Admiral J. H. Glennon will be\n?h?re to honor Franklin a? the Ameri\n?n Ambassador to France who bor-**\n?wed the money from that country\n?hich enabled John Paul Jone? to put\n?sea witb the infant United Stateit\n\"?le 15th New York Infantry, a negro\n?giment. Will pay its tribute to Frank?\nlin, not only as founder of the Penn-\ngyl'vania militia, bu-. as president of j\nthe first society for the abolition of j\nilEvery.\nA committee, headed by John Clyde\nOswald, will represent the New York\nCity E?nploving Printers' Association,\nwhich will hold its annual Franklin\ndinner to-morrow night at the Hotel\nAstor. The Sp.iinx Club and the\nAmerican Association of Advertising\nAgencies will have delegations at the\n?tatue to honor the man who very\nearly found out that advertising pays.\nA wrea-.h in the- shape of a kite will\nie laid by the New York Electrical\nSociety in commemoration of Poor\nRichard's revo utionizing the industrial j\nworld by bringing down power from the\nikies.\nCharles M, Schwab will be on hand\nfrith a wreath from the Pennsylvania j\nSociety, and Marcus M. Marks will have\na wr-ath of tribute from the National\nDaylight Saving Association, Franklin\nfirst having suggested that method of j\neconomizing time.\nThe fact that Franklin invented bi?\nfocal lenses for his own use will not\nbe forgotten by the American Associa- i\ntion of Wh.oiesa.e Opticians, while the\nMusic Industry Chamber of Com- I\ntnerce will remember that Ben invented I\nthe harmonica.\nPo3:ma.-ter Patten will attend in\nhonor of Franklin, the one-time Post\nmaster General. Street Cleaning Com-\nmissioner Leo will furnish a wreath in\nbehalf o? his department, Frank'in hav-\ning started street cleaning in Phila-\ndelphia.\nOther organizations to be represented\nare the University of Pennsylvania\nClub, the Collet? of William and Mary,\nYale and Ha-vard universities, the\nI. M. C. A., Sons of the Revolution,\nDaughters of the Revolution and the\n2d Federal Reserve Banking District.\nThe exercises will begin at 2:30.\nAt 9:30 to-morrow morning the Ben?\njamin Frank.in Memorial Committee\nwill place a wreath on Franklin's tablet\nin the Hail of Fame.\nAmherst Men Seek Truce\nWith Girls at Smith\njensim of Social Relations\nGrowg Serious With Senior\nHop Scheduled Feb. 12\nAMHERST. Mass,, Jan. 15. The\nyoung women of Smith College are at\nodds with the young men of Amherst\nCollege and the differences have caused\nsuspension of joint social activities.\nAttention was called to tfce break in\nrelations to-day by the action of Am?\nherst undergraduates in voting to take\nimmediate steps to make their peace\nwith the girls of Smith.\nIndividual efforts to restore old re?\nlations had met with some success, it\n?as said at the meeting, but Smith\nundergraduates as a body were still\nunderstoo? to regard Amherst men as\npersona n?n errata. Tn t'm<-. smokers j\nthought, the Smith girls would relent, i\nhut it was decided that Amherst should\ngo before Smith formally and at once j\nand ask that the sister college re-\n?tor? them to favor.\nAccordingly the student council was\ndirected to appoint a committee to i\npresent Amherst in a conference with\n?preaentatives of the girls of Smith, j\nSettlement ?*ar>no' corr\"' t'o s?*on for the I\nwen of Amherst, with the senior hop\n?*t for February 12 and the prospect\nthat no Smitb girls will grnce it. The\ncommittee was dirreted to begin nego?\ntiations at once and to report within\nten days.\nThe mptu-9 was declared by the\nSmith student body as an expression\nof resentment over references in an\nAmherst und?>r<*-r<iduate publication\nthat were regarded as uncomplimen?\ntary.\nViennese CnlWt?on of Old\nStr'nsef? ?n?trn?ne**it? Sold\nt Thirtv-tv-n old atrinired instrument*\n?\"?\"m the collection 0f th\" Society o*\n?h? Friends of \\T*isic in Vienna were\n'old at the Anderson Galleries vpste*\n?v ?ft-rnoon for a total of $7,848.50.\nAmone the seles were:\n1?y/n*ti',i rnn.tr-r violin with lab?t \"Anno\nAkiv lo B'\"\"*fenrl fere In Cremona\"; to\nmi-9,\"\" ?oi 'o' *\"00.\nham- i.-1*\"' vlo!l'' !atcd to Abra*\nOMG? db\"r*' foi* ***'2*>.\nmil toi? it-li ma*,ter violin; to Mr. Qold\n^Vi.nnf*. nia?er violin dated 1S07; to\nfis. Posner for $265.\nconnue master viola; to Mr. Powner for\n?o')?^o?'9nne?,* TtolonoeUo; to T. Mieracb\n,?f>l?WlMII\"*M vloloncell'W to A. R. Lout?\n?*?'i:3o.\"0nn*\"*\" v'**lone?I*o; to A. C. Roflt\n.01? 'u.'ir.\"-\"?^1 to A. R. LouU ?or I27?.\nlew violoncello; to P. Aokerman\nIl?Ol$if,0.r*',Ch TtoI<>ncollo; to A. L. Bmltta\nI,*'?w,|im v,olo**c*\"*oi to Edward Col\nConvict Found Innocent\nfeSSffc Dec* 2<-(By mail)\n*ft*r tlvin C* 27*~{By\na nu g r*'ore thitn fiftee?** y*-ars\nwhich il ?cntence for a murder of\n?\"Heent alway8 claimed to be\nNa??\\*Tng ,nan ??med Hirsch\nWt. having be /leased, the real cul\n0n ?Iln'? confessed.\n******ed h?!) y '?--?wing popular\nbods ?l1 at So,eure in Max. 190?\n'?and in XA ?T0.*-nB Sw'8* girl was\nsUtior, ^'Vng room of th?\nttfi PdfTh'lh/t6^ hKad been\n2 2? Previon. She had been seen\nI ????Vn? evemng in the company\nI dressed as a peasant\n?fe*. ?nd Ch?tUwT8 7rZhy y?*'\n?W*H to lif. L tr*e<i *nd sen\nFranklin Art Sale Completed\nReceipts Aggregate $36,390\nThe closing session of the sale of\nfurniture und art objects collected by\nthe late Mrs. Franklin Bartlett. at the\nAmerican Art Galleries yesterday after?\nnoon amounted to $15,241.60. The total\nfor the three sessions -was $S6,390.2&.\nAmong the sales of the day were:\nMahogany block front bureau. American\neighteenth century; to Mr. Pox for f 1,250.\nMahoirany bureau, American eighteenth\ncentury; to Mrs. Canning lor $800.\nCarve?\" mahoirany corner ohatr, HJngllnh\neighteenth century; to Ml?? Clarke for\n$$45.\nTwo Dutch marquetry chaira. Queen\nAnno period; to L. Joaepha for $230.\nFive carved mahogany chairs, Hepple\nwhlte period; to James Curran for $262.50.\nCarved and gilded convex mirror, Geor?\ngian period; to Mrs. Canning for $550.\nAmbusson tapestry suits, Ix>uls Philippe\nperiod, to Leo Elwyn for $430.\nMarquetry cheat on chest, to W. R.\nHearat for $750.\nCaucasian rug, to Miss A. F. Richard\n?on for $300.\nBerrebend rug, to Mr. Auvtn for $490.\nCarved portal and door, to W. R. Hearst\nfor $826.\nGerman Scheme to\nRaid U. S. Chemical\nMarket Is Charged\nTrade Organ Here Assert?\n18 Months9 Supply of So?\ndium Nitrate Has Been\nShipped In for Purpose\nGermany has struck her first blow\nfor the conquest of America's chemical\nmarket, according to information made\npublic yesterday by. Drug and Chemi?\ncal Markets, a publication devoted to\nthe interests of the chemical industry\nin this country, with offices at S Park\nPlace. The Dublication is headed by\nN. W. Haynos, an expert of many years'\nstanding in matters concerning the\nchemical industry.\nAccording to the information made\npublic by Mr. Haynes, Germany hat\nshipped to this country enough sodium\nnitrate to supply this country for th?\nnext fifteen or eighteen months. The\nshipment, it in declared, consists of\n4,611 casks, containing more than 2,600,\n000 pounds of nitrate. The nitrate, Mr.\nHaynes's publication asserts, has been\nshipped here by the Badische Anilin\nund-Soda Fabrik. It is in the care of\nKutroff, Pickhardt Co., agentB of the\nGerman concern, -who also have ob?\ntained the assistance of C. B. Peters\nCompany, Inc., of 110 Williams Street,\nfor the disposal of the nitrate to\nAmerican firms.\nDrug and Chemical Markets calls\nupon the United States government to\ntake such measures as will prevent the\nsuccessful execution of what the publi?\ncation regards as Germany's plan to\nobtain control of America's chemical\nindustry by underselling American\nfirms. According to information re?\nceived by Mr. Haynes's publication, the\nGerman nitrate is selling in this coun?\ntry at 6 cents a pound, a figure which\nMr. Havnes regards as ridiculously\nlow and offering no possibilities for\nsuccessful American competition.\nAccording to C. B. Peters Company,\nInc., the amount shipped here from\nGermany is not more than fifty tons.\nMr. Haynes's publication, how?*yer, in?\nsists that the amount given by C. B.\nPeters Company \"is an abbreviation\nfor 1,300 tons.\"\nAuto Show Closes\nAfter Serving as\nIndustrial Tonic\nExhibition Believed to Have\nBeen Turning Point From\nDepression to Prosperity;\nMany Sales During Week\nNew York's twenty-first annual Auto?\nmobile Show came to a close last night\nafter a week which in the opinion of\nthe management and the automobile\ntrade generally, has had a marked\neffect on the industry. It was expected\nthat the show would prove to be a I\nturning point from a period of business I\ndepression to one of prosperity and i\nits success seems to have justified that j\nhope.\n\"The show has been the best tonic I\never administered to the automobile\nindustry,\" said S. A. Miles, who man\naged the show for the National Auto?\nmobile Chamber of Commerce. \"Busi?\nness has responded splendidly. Thurs?\nday's paid attendance was within five\nhundred people of the best day on\nrecord the corresponding day of last\nyear. Makers and salesmen who came\ndiscouraged are now completely changed\nand confident of satisfactory business.\nMuny pood sales have been made and\nprospects are in satisfactory numbers.\n\"Our advertising plan designed to\nencourage belief in the imminence of\na revival of business, combined with\nthe utility of our automobiles, haa been\nentirely successful. It all means that,\nas in 1907 and 1914, the automobile in?\ndustry is the first to feel the public\npulse and will lead again in the return\nof prosperity.\"\nWith the 1921 New York show ended,\nmanufacturers and dealers are turning\ntheir attention to Chicago, where the\nsecond of the national motor car expo?\nsitions will open at the Coliseum and\n1st Regiment Armory on January 29\nand continue until February 5.\nThe work of removing the 400 ex?\nhibits was started at the close of the\nshow last night with a rush, so tha*.\nthe Grand Central Palace could be\nmade ready for the installation of the\nI.\n'displays for National Marine League\nWeek. The latter ?how will open Jan?\nuary 24 and will be the largest exhi?\nbition of marine craft ever staged in\nthis city.\na\nMore Rigid Motor Laws\nAre Asked by Merchants\nAssociation Would Amend State\nStatutes to Make Highways\nSafe for Pedestrians\nThe Merchants' Association made\npublic yesterday suggestions by its\ncommittee on city conditions and ordi?\nnances designed to make the highways\nsafer for pedestrians and motorists.\nAccompanying the report of the com?\nmittee are drafts of proposed amend?\nments to the state automobile law\nwhich the Merchants' Association will\ntry to have passed.\nIn drawing up the proposed amend?\nments the committee's intention was to\ngive the Secretary of State broader\npowers as to the issuance of drivers'\nlicenses and their revocation.\n\"Effective tests for all applicants for\nlicenses,\" the committee says in its\nreport, \"and their subsequent effeetiy*\nregulation through inquiry, when oe\ncasion arises, into the facts attending\nail accidents, with a view to the* wit*,\nI drawal of the privilege of operatic**\nwhin required by the public safety,\nwould make necessary a larce staff an?J\na high degree of organization in th<\nAuto Bureau of the Secretary of State,\ni Stringent provisions of law will bjj\nthemselves have little effect *n remov*>\ning evils, and it is, therefore, the duty\nof the Legislature to provide the mean*\nfor the machinery and tLc organization\nessential to produce the result in-?\ntended, namely, the enforcement oi\nlaws adapted to secure the protection\nof the public.\n\"To this end, in order to enable thi\nSecretary of State effectively to ad?\nminister the law with whose enforce?\nment he is charged, it will require a\ngreat increase in the number of em?\nployees assigned for the purpose in?\ndicated, and due provision should be\nmade by the Legislature for that pur-.\npose.\n\"The revenues derivable from driv?\ners' licenses are amply sufficient? t?\nprovide for these expenses and, fos\nwhatever extent is necessary, such\nrevenues should be made available to\nprovide adequate machinery for an*\nforcement of the law.\"\niiiiiiiiiiiriiiiiiriiriiiiriiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiii\nFlint\n9s Fine Furniture\n-4&EP.\nA\nRECORD VALUE-GIVING SALE\nPositively disregarding replacement cost\nWe intend to make this event conspicuous for\nits absolute sincerity and for the truly exceptional\ndesirability of the merchandise. Those who have\nopportunity for comparison are urged to use it.\nEvery article is from our own regular stock. The\nprices, already low in their relation to the\nquality of our goods, are now at the very lowest\nextreme?and further than that\n!?^?i?4?^ THAT NOTHING BOUGHT AT THIS SALE WILL BE SOLD FOR\n^J^W?,^S^ M?^r^^JEAR* EVERY PRICE IS LOWER THAN MANUFACTURING COSTS\nARE LJKELY TO WARRANT FOR MORE THAN A YEAR TO COME. IF FOR ANY REASON WE QUOTE\nA LOWER PRICE, WE WILL RETURN EVERY PURCHASER THE AMOUNT OF THAT DIFFERENCE.\nRandom Se